25|$|Emancipation {{remained}} by {{no means}} a foregone conclusion {{at the start of the}} war, though events soon began to move against slaveholding interests in Maryland. On December 16, 1861 a bill was presented to Congress to emancipate enslaved people in Washington, D.C., and in March 1862 Lincoln held talks with Marylanders on the subject of emancipation. Marylanders like Representative John Crisfield resisted the President, arguing that freedom would be worse for the slaves than slavery, though <b>such</b> <b>arguments</b> became increasingly ineffective as the war progressed.|$|E
